Ad Text:
Employment Type: Full Time Ongoing
Remuneration: $113K -$123K depending on experience+ 17% superannuation (Level 7)
Location: Kensington UNSW Campus (hybrid)

Why Your Role Matters

The Insights and Performance Analyst enables data-driven decision-making across The Nucleus: Student Hub by delivering actionable insights, analytics, and performance reporting. This role supports service improvement, strategic planning, and operational efficiency through data analysis, performance evaluation, and evidence-based recommendations.

You will contribute to the design of performance frameworks, service evaluation processes, and continuous improvement initiatives that enhance the student experience. The position reports to the Lead, Hub Operations, and has no direct reports.

Main Responsibilities

Collect, analyse, and interpret data on student services, including enquiry trends, service delivery, wait times, satisfaction scores, and case outcomes.
Develop and maintain dashboards and performance reports that support leadership decision-making and service optimisation.
Collaborate with Hub staff and leaders to identify performance gaps, process inefficiencies, and opportunities for innovation.
Contribute to the design and implementation of KPIs, benchmarking, and service evaluation frameworks.
Conduct root-cause analyses to support issue resolution and continuous improvement.
Provide data-driven insights and recommendations to inform operational and workforce planning.
Ensure data accuracy, consistency, and integrity across all reporting.

Who You Are

We are looking for someone who is aligned with UNSW’s vision and values and comes with:

Demonstrated experience in data analysis, business intelligence, or performance reporting, or equivalent expertise.
Proven ability to gather, interpret, and present complex data to support decision-making in a service-focused environment.
High-level proficiency with data visualisation tools and Microsoft Excel; experience with analytics platforms is an advantage.
Strong analytical and problem-solving skills with the ability to translate data into actionable insights.
Excellent written and verbal communication skills, with the ability to present findings clearly to non-technical audiences.
Demonstrated ability to work both independently and collaboratively in a fast-paced, complex environment.
Experience in a customer- or student-focused setting, with a commitment to service excellence and continuous improvement.

Candidates will need to have ongoing working rights – this role is not available for sponsorship.

Benefits and Culture: People are at the core of everything we do. We recognise it is the contributions of our staff who make UNSW one of the best universities in Australia and the world.  Our benefits include: 

Access to up to 17% Superannuation contributions and additional leave loading payments 
Flexible working arrangements
Additional 3 days of leave over the end of the year period 
Discounts and entitlements (retail, education, fitness)

Recruitment process: Please submit your resume as well as cover letter that addresses the points in the “who you are” section of the job ad.

You can send via the ‘Apply Now’ button. A copy of the Position Description can be found on JOBS@UNSW.

Applications close:  Wednesday 26th November before 11:55pm

Get in touch for any question or support:

Kim Symons – Talent Acquisition – k.symons@unsw.edu.au

Applications cannot be accepted if sent directly to the contact listed

UNSW is committed to equity diversity and inclusion. Applications from women, people of culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds, those living with disabilities, members of the LGBTIQ+ community; and people of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander descent, are encouraged. UNSW provides workplace adjustments for people with disability, and access to flexible work options for eligible staff. The University reserves the right not to proceed with any appointment.

Frontier - business overview
 
Frontier Advisors is Australia's leading independent asset consultant. Frontier has been at the forefront of delivering investment advice and technology to institutional investors for more than 25 years. We work to help our client's advance prosperity for their beneficiaries.
 
Key Responsibilities

 Knowledge/Skills/Experience

Background:

This Department plays a fundamental role underpinning the Australian economy by maintaining and regulating Australia’s measurement system, developing and maintaining national measurement standards, and delivering world-class measurement products and client services. 

Measurement is integral to a successful economy and to the progress of innovation and science. The work supports the productivity and growth of Australian industries, and aims to ensure a fair, safe, healthy and competitive Australia. We provide assurance that Australia’s measurement system is fit for purpose and evolves in line with advances in science and technology and with the changing measurement needs of their stakeholders in government, industry, business, and research.

The branch where this role is situated plays an important role in ensuring Australian consumers and industry can rely on trusted measurements for fair trade in goods and services.  To ensure traders comply with the law and adopt correct measurement trading practices, we employ Trade Measurement Inspectors who check that measuring instruments (for example, weighing instruments, fuel dispensers and weighbridges) are accurate, and pre-packaged articles contain the correct amount of produce.

The Role:

Reporting to the Manager, Programs and Digital, the Risk Analyst will work collaboratively with internal and external stakeholders to build and embed an effective risk framework for all branch activities. You will work collaboratively across all sections of the branch and work closely with the Departments risk teams.

The role will focus on the development of a single, clearly articulated risk framework covering all branch activities. This will include the review of existing, and the development of new policies, procedures, templates and tools.

BASELINE SECURITY CLEARANCE NEEDED AS A MINIMUM

The Risk Analyst operates under broad direction and will be responsible for the following:

1.      Develop and implement a comprehensive risk management framework.

2.      Develop and review policies, procedures, risk management tools and templates.

3.      Manage, deliver and monitor projects.

4.      Share knowledge within the branch and the Department to improve risk maturity.

5.      Foster an environment of continuous improvement by keeping abreast of industry and government best practice and proactively engaging with stakeholders to deliver outcomes.

6.      Demonstrate behaviour according to APS code of conduct and department standards and participate fully in all aspects of WH&S

Key Capabilities:

The capabilities listed below describe the specific skills, knowledge and behaviours required to successfully perform this job role:

1.      Demonstrated ability to develop and implement effective risk frameworks within a government or regulatory setting, including the development of policies, procedures, templates and tools.

2.      Demonstrated experience in developing and leading projects across multiple business units. 

3.      Highly developed written and oral communication skills, including a demonstrated ability to document and present complex risk information in a clear and concise manner.

4.      Demonstrated ability to develop and maintain strong productive and collaborative working relationships with stakeholders.

5.      Well-developed skills in research, analysis and problem-solving.

6.      Sound knowledge of, or the ability to rapidly acquire a sound knowledge of branch activities, legislation, resource management guides, policies and procedures.

Mandatory Requirements:

·       Australian Citizenship.

·       BASELINE SECURITY CLEARANCE NEEDED AS A MINIMUM

Desirable Requirements:

·       A relevant degree or higher qualification.

·       Project Management qualifications and/or experience.

·       Experience in contemporary database interrogation, analysis and reporting software.

·       Ability to quickly gain sound operational knowledge of Acts and associated regulations.

The Organisation:

Mars has partnered with a growth business to appoint an experienced senior financial analyst/finance lead to play a key role in the integration of recently acquired businesses.

The ideal candidate will bring strong technical finance expertise, proven success in M&A integration or large-scale finance transformation, and the leadership skills to build and manage a high performing finance team.

The Role:

Reporting to the Chief Financial Officer, the roles responsibilities will include but are not limited to the following:

Deliver accurate and timely management reports, financial analysis, and commentary to support senior decision-making.
Lead annual budgeting and periodic forecasting processes in collaboration with business unit leaders, ensuring alignment with strategic goals.
Partner across Operations, Sales, HR, and Corporate Development to provide commercial insights and improve business performance.
Support mergers and acquisitions, including financial due diligence, post-acquisition integration, and tracking of synergy realisation.
Develop and maintain financial models, dashboards, and analytical tools to enhance visibility of key business drivers.
Identify opportunities for process improvement and system optimisation across the finance function.
Ensure compliance with Australian Accounting Standards and maintain strong governance and internal controls.
Present financial insights clearly and effectively to senior and non-financial stakeholders, influencing strategic decisions.

The Requirements:

Fully qualified accountant (CA, CPA, CIMA or equivalent).
Strong technical accounting and financial reporting background, ideally gained within a multi-entity organisation.
Demonstrated experience in M&A integration, post-acquisition finance, or large transformation initiatives.
Exceptional stakeholder management and influencing skills, with the confidence to engage at senior leadership and board levels.
Strategic thinker with a hands-on, delivery-focused approach.
Strong analytical and problem-solving capability, with a focus on value creation and operational excellence.
